{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "As a result, AUC as a evaluation metric has a dedicated history not only for model evaluation but also for medical screening test such as early cancer detection [18], bankruptcy prediction [19], software defect prediction [20], and many other purposes [21] [22] [23], albeit the use of AUC has faced more scrutiny recently [24] [25] [26] [27].",
    "Critics of AUC have pointed out at least two issues associated with its use: it does not account for prevalence and does not work well with imbalanced data where either the positive or the negative class overwhelmingly dominates the AUC score [28] [29] [30]; not all regions of AUC are meaningful or represent realistic evaluation outcomes [31] [32] [33].",
    "As a result, a number of alternatives have been proposed.",
    "For example, Matthew's correlation coefficient (MCC) has been proposed as a better alternative because it has high values only when a model predicts well on both positive and negative classes [7, 8, 12, 34].",
    "Additional proposed alternatives to the standard AUC include: average positive predictive value (AP) that varies with respect to prevalence in the data and places more emphasis on early positives than does AUC [35]; uniform AUC to make AUC not dependent on the range of predicted values [36]; not proper ROC Curve to identify hidden subclass in microarray data [37]; restricted ROC Curves to separate informative from noninformative values [38]; concentrated AUC to address the early retrieval problem [39]; partial AUC metrics [40, 41]; delimited region of interest in the ROC space [32, 33]; total operating characteristic [42]; expected cost representation [43]; precision-recall curve to better suit low-prevalence data [30, 44]; general performance score to combine several user-selected metrics [9, 45], etc."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "As a result, AUC as a evaluation metric has a dedicated history not only for model evaluation but also for medical screening test such as early cancer detection [18], bankruptcy prediction [19], software defect prediction [20], and many other purposes [21] [22] [23], albeit the use of AUC has faced more scrutiny recently [24] [25] [26] [27].",
    "Critics of AUC have pointed out at least two issues associated with its use: it does not account for prevalence and does not work well with imbalanced data where either the positive or the negative class overwhelmingly dominates the AUC score [28] [29] [30]; not all regions of AUC are meaningful or represent realistic evaluation outcomes [31] [32] [33].",
